<h1 id="introduction">Introduction</h1>

<p>Docker is a container virtualization environment that can establish development or runtime environments without modifying the base operating system environment. It has the ability to deploy container instances that provide virtualization using the host kernel, which makes it faster and lighter than full hardware virtualization.
Versions</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Docker.io</strong> - Older versions of Docker were called docker-engine or docker.io. The docker-io package was the name used in Debian / Ubuntu. That reference no longer exists.</li>
  <li><strong>Docker CE</strong> - It is the free version of Docker that stands for Docker Community Edition.</li>
  <li><strong>Docker EE</strong> - It is the paid version of Docker and has more features. It means Docker Entreprise Edition.</li>
</ul>

<blockquote>
  <p>Containers that produce Kernel Panic will induce Kernel Panic in the host’s operating system.</p>
</blockquote>

